Great question 🔥 — this shows you’re thinking deeply.

First important clarification:

In RSpec, expect itself does NOT have many methods.

expect returns an ExpectationTarget, and the methods like:

eq

eql

be

receive

change

are called matchers.

So what you’re really asking is:

“What matchers are available in RSpec?”

Now — RSpec has MANY matchers (dozens). I’ll give you a structured, categorized list of the most important and commonly used ones (the ones interviewers expect you to know).

🧠 1️⃣ Equality Matchers
eq

Uses ==

expect(5).to eq(5)
eql

Uses eql? (stricter)

expect(5).to eql(5)
equal

Checks object identity (same object in memory)

expect(obj1).to equal(obj2)
🧠 2️⃣ Comparison Matchers
expect(10).to be > 5
expect(10).to be >= 10
expect(5).to be < 10
expect(5).to be <= 5
expect(5).to be_between(1, 10)
🧠 3️⃣ Truthiness / Boolean
expect(value).to be_truthy
expect(value).to be_falsey
expect(value).to be true
expect(value).to be false
expect(value).to be_nil
🧠 4️⃣ Collection Matchers
expect([1,2,3]).to include(2)
expect([1,2,3]).to contain_exactly(1,2,3)
expect([1,2,3]).to match_array([3,2,1])
expect([1,2,3]).to start_with(1)
expect([1,2,3]).to end_with(3)
🧠 5️⃣ String Matchers
expect("hello").to match(/ell/)
expect("hello").to start_with("he")
expect("hello").to end_with("lo")
🧠 6️⃣ Predicate Matchers

RSpec automatically supports Ruby predicate methods.

If object has:

user.valid?

You can write:

expect(user).to be_valid

Other examples:

expect(user).to be_admin
expect(order).to be_paid

It calls admin?, paid?.

🧠 7️⃣ Change Matcher (Very Important)

Used for side effects.

expect {
  user.increment!(:balance)
}.to change { user.balance }.by(1)

Other forms:

.to change(Model, :count).by(1)
.to change { something }.from(0).to(1)
🧠 8️⃣ Raise Error
expect {
  some_method
}.to raise_error

More specific:

expect {
  some_method
}.to raise_error(ArgumentError)
🧠 9️⃣ Respond To
expect(user).to respond_to(:name)
🧠 🔟 Type Matchers
expect(user).to be_a(User)
expect(user).to be_an_instance_of(User)
expect(user).to be_kind_of(Object)
🧠 1️⃣1️⃣ Yield Matchers

For blocks:

expect { |b| method(&b) }.to yield_control
expect { |b| method(&b) }.to yield_with_args(1,2)
🧠 1️⃣2️⃣ Output Matcher
expect {
  puts "hello"
}.to output("hello\n").to_stdout
🧠 1️⃣3️⃣ Throw Symbol
expect {
  throw :done
}.to throw_symbol(:done)
🧠 1️⃣4️⃣ Interaction Matchers (Mocks)
expect(object).to receive(:method)
expect(object).to have_received(:method)

With extras:

.receive(:method).with(arg)
.receive(:method).once
.receive(:method).twice
.receive(:method).exactly(3).times
🧠 1️⃣5️⃣ Compound Matchers
expect(user).to be_valid.and have_attributes(name: "Shubham")

Or:

expect(number).to be > 5.and be < 20
🧠 1️⃣6️⃣ Satisfy (Custom Condition)
expect(10).to satisfy { |n| n.even? }
🧠 1️⃣7️⃣ Have Attributes
expect(user).to have_attributes(name: "Shubham", age: 25)
🚀 Most Important Matchers (Focus For Interviews)

If you master these, you’re solid:

eq

be

be_nil

include

change

raise_error

respond_to

receive

have_received

be_a / be_instance_of

🎯 Final Important Note

RSpec also allows:

expect(value).not_to eq(5)

So every matcher works with not_to.

⚠️ Important Reality

There are MANY more matchers and custom ones.

You can also create your own matcher using:

RSpec::Matchers.define

But for interviews and daily Rails work, the list above is what really matters.

